## Problem 1

``` r
library(p8105.datasets)
data("ny_noaa")
```

The NY NOAA dataset contains 2595176 rows and 7 columns. Variables
include weather station id, date, precipitation, snowfall, snow depth,
and min and max temperature.

``` r
ny_noaa %>% 
  count(snow) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))
```

``` r
# data cleaning
ny_noaa = 
  ny_noaa %>% 
  separate(date, into = c("year", "month", "day"), convert = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(
    tmax = as.numeric(tmax),
    tmin = as.numeric(tmin))
```

We find that 0 is the most commonly observed value for snowfall. This is
because most days of the year, it does not snow at all in NY. The second
most commonly observed value is `NA`, indicating missingness.

``` r
ny_noaa %>% 
  group_by(id, year, month) %>% 
  filter(month %in% c(1, 7)) %>% 
  summarize(mean_tmax = mean(tmax, na.rm = TRUE, color = id)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = mean_tmax, group = id)) + geom_point() + geom_path() +
  facet_grid(~month) +
  labs(title = "Mean monthly temperature for each station across years for January and July")
```

The mean temperature in January is much lower than the mean temperature

across the years. We do see one uncharacteristically cold station in
July of 1987 or 1988, as well as a few other less drastic outliers.

Make a two-panel plot showing (i) tmax vs tmin for the full dataset; and
(ii) make a plot showing the distribution of snowfall values greater
than 0 and less than 100 separately by year.

``` r
hex = 
  ny_noaa %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = tmin, y = tmax)) + 
  geom_hex()

ridge = 
  ny_noaa %>% 
  filter(snow < 100, snow > 0) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = snow, y = as.factor(year))) + 
  geom_density_ridges()

hex + ridge
```

## Problem 2

First, load, tidy, merge, and organize the data sets. I excluded
participants less than 21 years of age, and those with missing
demographic data; I also encoded data with reasonable variable classes.

``` r
accel = read_csv("./nhanes/nhanes_accel.csv")
```

``` r
combined_data = inner_join(covar, accel, by = "SEQN") %>%
  janitor::clean_names() %>%
  filter(age >= 21) %>%
  mutate(sex = if_else(sex == 1, "male", "female")) %>%
  mutate(education = case_when(
    education == 1 ~ "Less than high school",
    education == 2 ~ "High school equivalent",
    education == 3 ~ "More than high school"
  )) %>%
  mutate(sex = factor(sex, levels = c("male","female"), ordered = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(education = factor(education, levels = c("Less than high school", "High school equivalent", "More than high school"), ordered = TRUE))  %>%
  filter(!is.na(sex) & !is.na(age) & !is.na(bmi) & !is.na(education))

combined_data
```

From the table, we can conclude that the numbers of men and women in

``` r

  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Age Distributions by Sex and Education",
       x = "Education Level",
       y = "Age") +

age_distribution_plot
```

We can see from the boxplot that in ‘Less than high school’ and ‘More

are close, but in ‘High school equivalent’ level, age distribution by
sex is quite different, female age median is much greater than male age
median.

Plot total activities (y-axis) against age (x-axis); this plot compares
men to women, have separate panels for each education level and include
a trend line.

``` r
# calculate the total activity
total_act = combined_longer %>%
  group_by(seqn,sex,age,education) %>%
  summarise(total = sum(min_activity)) 
```

    ## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'seqn', 'sex', 'age'. You can override
    ## using the `.groups` argument.

``` r
act_plot = ggplot(total_act, aes(x = age, y = total, color = sex)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ education) +
  labs(title = "Total Activity by Age, Sex, and Education Level",
       x = "Age",
       y = "Total Activity") +
  theme_minimal()

act_plot
```

    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

![](p8105_hw3_zz3309_files/figure-gfm/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png)<!-- -->

From the plot, it can be concluded that: in three education levels, the
overall trend of total activity is decreasing as age increase, although
sometimes total activity increases while age increases. In the three
education levels,when it comes to the age of 80, men and women have
similar total activity level. In ‘Less than high school’ level, the
speed that total activity decreases as age increases is faster than that
in the other two education levels.

Make a three-panel plot that shows the 24-hour activity time courses for
each education level and use color to indicate sex.

``` r
combined_longer_new = combined_longer %>%
  mutate(time_min = as.numeric(gsub("min", "", time_min))) %>%
  arrange(time_min)

plot_24h = ggplot(combined_longer_new, aes(x = time_min, y = min_activity, color = sex)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~ education, nrow = 2) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "24-hour Activity Time Courses for Each Education Level and Sex",
       x = "Time",
       y = "Activity")+
  theme_minimal()

plot_24h
```

    ## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

![](p8105_hw3_zz3309_files/figure-gfm/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png)<!-- -->

It can be concluded that the trend lines for male and female are very
alike, which indicates that there are no significant differences for
their 24-hour activity between sex. The trends in three education levels
are similar too, indicating there are no significant difference for
24-hour activity among the three education levels.

## Problem 3

First import, clean, and tidy citi data, then describe the resulting
dataset.

``` r
jan_2020 <- read.csv("./citibike/Jan 2020 Citi.csv") %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(2020), month = as.factor(1)) %>%
  janitor::clean_names() 

jan_2024 <- read.csv("./citibike/Jan 2024 Citi.csv") %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(2024), month = as.factor(1)) %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

july_2020 <- read.csv("./citibike/July 2020 Citi.csv") %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(2020), month = as.factor(7)) %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

july_2024 <- read.csv("./citibike/July 2024 Citi.csv") %>%
  mutate(year = as.factor(2024), month = as.factor(7)) %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

citi_clean <- bind_rows(jan_2020,jan_2024,july_2020,july_2024) %>%
  mutate(
    rideable_type = as.factor(rideable_type),
    member_casual = as.factor(member_casual),
    start_station_name = as.factor(start_station_name),
    end_station_name = as.factor(end_station_name),
    weekdays = as.factor(weekdays),
    duration = as.numeric(duration)
  ) %>%
  na.omit()

citi_clean
```

The resulting dataset contains 99253 rows and 9 columns. Variables
include ride_id, rideable_type, weekdays, duration, start_station_name,
end_station_name, member_casual, year and month. I created year and
month variables so that I can distinguish the time of each observation.

Produce a reader-friendly table showing the total number of rides in
each combination of year and month separating casual riders and Citi
Bike members.

``` r
summary_table <- citi_clean %>%
  group_by(year, month , member_casual) %>%
  summarise(total_rides = n()) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = member_casual, values_from = total_rides, names_prefix = "count_")
```

    ## `.groups` argument.

We can see that in both 2020 and 2024, there are more rides in July than
in January, maybe it is because it is warmer in July, Moreover, in every
combination of year and month, the number of rides from Citi Bike
members is much greater than that from casual riders.

Make a table showing the 5 most popular starting stations for July 2024;
include the number of rides originating from these stations.

``` r

  filter(year == 2024, month == 7) %>%

  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>%
```

Make a plot to investigate the effects of day of the week, month, and
year on median ride duration.

``` r
duration_plot <- citi_clean %>%
  mutate(weekdays = factor(weekdays, levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) %>%
  group_by(year, month, weekdays) %>%
  summarise(median_duration = median(duration)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = weekdays, y = median_duration, fill = month)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  labs(title = "Median Ride Duration by Weekday, Month, and Year",
       x = "Weekday", y = "Median Duration", fill = "Month")
```

    ## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the
    ## `.groups` argument.

``` r
duration_plot
```

![](p8105_hw3_zz3309_files/figure-gfm/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png)<!-- -->

It is obvious that in 2020, the median duration in every combination of
month and weekday is greater than that of 2024, this indicates that in
2020, the overall median duration of rides may be longer than that of
2024. For month as a factor, July determines a longer median duration
compared with January. In 2020, no matter the month, on Saturdays and
Sundays, the median duration are the longest in a week. In July of 2024,
the situation is the same.

For data in 2024, make a figure that shows the impact of month,
membership status, and bike type on the distribution of ride duration.

``` r
duration_distribution_plot <- citi_clean %>%
  filter(year == 2024) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = rideable_type, y = duration, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~month) +
  labs(title = "Ride Duration Distribution by Month, Membership Status, and Bike Type",
       x = "Bike Type", y = "Duration", fill = "Membership Status")

duration_distribution_plot
```

![](p8105_hw3_zz3309_files/figure-gfm/unnamed-chunk-16-1.png)<!-- -->

The boxplots of January and July look similar, so month may not affect
the ride duration distribution. However, we can conclude that casual
riders tend to ride both types of bikes longer than Citi Bike members.
Moreover, for Citi Bike members, their ride duration for electric bikes
is longer than that for classic bikes, but for casual riders, their ride
duration for classic bikes is longer than that for electric bikes.
